<section xml:id="section-slope">
    <title>Slope</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-exploring-two-variable-data-and-rate-of-change">Section</xref> we observed that data with constant rates of change between points leads to a straight-line graph. This section explores that more.</p>
        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="MeU-KzdCBps" />
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>What is slope?</title>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
            <p>With data where the <term>rate of change</term> from point to point never changes, we observed in <xref ref="section-exploring-two-variable-data-and-rate-of-change">Section</xref> that the data points must fall in a straight line, as in <xref ref="figure-constant-rate-of-change">Figure</xref>. We mentioned that this situation means there is a <term>linear relationship</term> between the two variables.</p>
            <figure xml:id="figure-constant-rate-of-change">
                <caption>Between successive data points the rate of change is always <m>1/2</m>.</caption>
                <image>
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[clip=false]
                            \addplot+[] {0.5*x+1};
                            \addplot[] coordinates {(-6,-2) (-4,-1)} node[pos=0.50, pin=-60:{rate $\frac{1}{2}$}]{};
                            \addplot[] coordinates {(-4,-1) (0,1)} node[pos=0.50, pin=120:{rate $\frac{2}{4}=\frac{1}{2}$}]{};
                            \addplot[] coordinates {(0,1) (6,4)} node[pos=0.50, pin=80:{rate $\frac{3}{6}=\frac{1}{2}$}]{};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-6,-2) (-4, -1) (0,1) (6,4)};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>If the rates of change are all the same, this merits giving a special name to that common rate of change.</p>

        <definition xml:id="definition-slope">
            <title>Slope</title>
            <index><main>slope</main></index>
            <statement>
                <p>When <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are two variables where the rate of change between any two data points is always the same, we call this common rate of change the <term>slope</term>. Since having a constant rate of change means the graph will be a straight line, it's also called the <term>slope of the line</term>.</p>

                <p>Considering the definition for <xref ref="definition-rate-of-change">Definition</xref>, this means that you can calculate slope, <m>m</m>, as <men xml:id="equation-slope-definition">m=\frac{\text{change in $y$}}{\text{change in $x$}}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</men> when <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> have a linear relationship.</p>

                <p>A slope is a rate of change. So if there are units on the horizontal and vertical variables, then there will be units on the slope. The slope will be measured in <m>\frac{\text{vertical units}}{\text{horizontal units}}</m>.</p>

                <p>If the slope is nonzero, we say that there is a <term>linear relationship</term> between <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.<index><main>linear relationship</main></index><index><main>relationship</main><sub>linear</sub></index> When the slope is <m>0</m>, we say that <m>y</m> is <term>constant</term> with respect to <m>x</m>.<index><main>constant</main></index></p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <p>Here are some scenarios with different slopes. Note that a slope is more meaningful with units.<ul>
            <li>
                <p>If a tree grows <m>2.5</m> feet every year, it's rate of change in height is the same from year to year. So the height and time have a linear relationship where the <term>slope</term> is <quantity><mag>2.5</mag><unit base="foot" /><per base="year" /></quantity>.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>If a company loses <m>2</m> million dollars every year, it's rate of change in reserve funds is the same from year to year. So the company's reserve funds and time have a linear relationship where the <term>slope</term> is <m>-2</m> million dollars per year.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>If Cara has stopped growing, her rate of change in height is the same from year to year<mdash />it's zero. So the <term>slope</term> is <quantity><mag>0</mag><unit base="inch" /><per base="year" /></quantity>. Cara's height is <term>constant</term> with respect to time. Height and time don't really have a relationship at all, since height doesn't depend on time.</p>
            </li>
        </ul></p>

        <remark>
            <p>A useful phrase for remembering the definition of <term>slope</term> is <q>rise over run</q>. Here, <q>rise</q> refers to <m>\Delta y</m> and <q>run</q> refers to <m>\Delta x</m>. Be careful though. As we have learned, the horizontal direction comes <em>first</em> in mathematics, followed by the vertical direction. The phrase <q>rise over run</q> reverses this. (It's a bit awkward to say, but the phrase <q>run under rise</q> puts the horizontal change first.)</p>
        </remark>

        <aside>
            <title>Slope <m>m</m></title>
            <p>Why is the letter <m>m</m> commonly used to stand for <q>slope</q>? Some believe that it comes from the French word <q>monter</q> which means <q>to climb</q>. And French has a special place in this topic because Decartes was French. Interestingly, there are reports of French algebra classrooms using <m>s</m> to stand for slope. When asked why, some say that it's because of the <em>English</em> word <q>slope.</q></p>
        </aside>


        <example>
            <title>Matthew's Savings</title>
            <p>On <abbr>Dec.</abbr> 31, Matthew found that he had only <m>\$50</m> dollars left in his savings account. He decided to save <m>\$20</m> dollars per week in the new year, depositing it into his account, and not spend anything from this account. What is happening with his account balance over time? This example examines the account balance and slope from a variety of perspectives. There's no punchline here, just a lot to think about.</p>

            <p>The savings account balance is growing week by week, with a steady rate of <m>\$20</m> per week. Since the rate of change is steady, we can say the <term>slope</term> is <m>\$20</m> per week according to <xref ref="definition-slope">Definition</xref>.</p>

            <p>We can model the amount of money in his savings account after <m>x</m> weeks with an equation. Since Matthew started with <m>\$50</m> and adds <m>\$20</m> for each of the <m>x</m> weeks that have passed, the account balance <m>y</m> is <men xml:id="equation-matthews-savings">y=50+20x</men> where <m>y</m> is a dollar amount. The number in front of <m>x\text{,}</m> <m>20\text{,}</m> is the <term>slope</term> we just identified. (Well, almost; with its units, the slope is <m>\$20</m> per week.)</p>

            <p>Let's build a table to model the amount of money Matthew saves.</p>

            <table xml:id="table-matthews-savings">
                <caption>Matthew's savings</caption>
                <tabular>
                    <col halign="center"/>
                    <col halign="center"/>
                    <col halign="center"/>
                    <col halign="center"/>
                    <row bottom="medium">
                        <cell/>
                        <cell><line><m>x</m>, weeks since</line><line><abbr>Dec.</abbr> 31</line></cell>
                        <cell><line><m>y</m>, savings account</line><line>balance (dollars)</line></cell>
                        <cell/>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>50</m></cell>
                        <cell/>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>x</m> increases by <m>1</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>70</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m><m>y</m> increases by <m>20</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>x</m> increases by <m>1</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>90</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m><m>y</m> increases by <m>20</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>x</m> increases by <m>2</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>130</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m><m>y</m> increases by <m>40</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>x</m> increases by <m>3</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>190</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m><m>y</m> increases by <m>60</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>x</m> increases by <m>5</m><m>\longrightarrow</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>12</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>290</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\longleftarrow</m><m>y</m> increases by <m>100</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>

            <p>Matthew saves <m>20</m> dollars per week; as a result, in the first two rows of <xref ref="table-matthews-savings">Table</xref>, when <m>x</m> increases by <m>1\text{,}</m> <m>y</m> increases by <m>20\text{.}</m> So the <term>slope</term> is making another appearance: in a table of data from a linear relationship, whenever <m>x</m> increases by <m>1</m> unit, <m>y</m> increases by the slope.</p>

            <p>In the table's later rows, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> increase by larger amounts. For example in the the last row, <m>x</m> has increased by <m>5\text{,}</m> while <m>y</m> has increased by <m>100\text{.}</m> The rate of change is <m>\frac{100}{5}=20\text{,}</m> which again is the <term>slope</term>. (We're not surprised, because that's what <xref ref="definition-slope">Defintion</xref> told us it would be.)</p>

            <p>What does a graph of <xref ref="equation-matthews-savings">Equation</xref> look like? We can use data from <xref ref="table-matthews-savings">Table</xref>. The resulting picure is of a straight line. We call the triangles in <xref ref="figure-matthews-savings">figure</xref> <term>slope triangles</term><index><main>slope</main><sub>triangle</sub></index>, because each one of them can tell us the line's slope.</p>

            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">

                <figure xml:id="figure-matthews-savings">
                    <caption>Matthew's savings</caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={weeks},
                                        ylabel={savings (in dollars)},
                                        xmin=-1,xmax=15,
                                        ymin=-20,ymax=320,
                                        xtick={2,4,...,14},
                                        minor xtick={1,2,...,15},
                                        ytick={100,200,300},
                                        minor ytick={20,40,...,320},
                                        ]
                                \addplot+[domain = 0:13,->]{50+20*x};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,50) (1,70) (2,90) (4,130) (7,190) (12,290)};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,50) (1,50) (1,65)};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(1,70) (2,70) (2,85)};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(2,90) (4,90) (4,125)};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(4,130) (7,130) (7,185)};
                                \addplot[guideline,-] coordinates {(7,190) (12,190)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$5$ weeks};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(12,190) (12,285)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90] {$\$100$};
                            \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <paragraphs>
                    <p>The small slope triangle on the far left side indicates when <m>1</m> week passes, <m>20</m> dollars are saved. The rate of change there is <m>\frac{20}{1}=20</m> dollars per week, the <term>slope</term>.</p>
                    <p>The large slope triangle on the far right side indicates when <m>5</m> weeks pass, <m>100</m> dollars are saved. The rate of change there is <m>\frac{100}{5}=20</m> dollars per week, <em>still</em> equal to the <term>slope</term>.</p>
                </paragraphs>
            </sidebyside>


            <p>Both slope triangles lead to the same slope. And so we have yet <em>another</em> way to think about/compute <term>slope</term>. We can choose any two points on the line, draw a slope triangle, and then calculate the <q>rise over run</q>.</p>

            <p>We could have drawn the slope triangle in a different way:</p>

            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
                <figure>
                    <caption>Matthew's savings</caption>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={weeks},
                                        ylabel={savings (in dollars)},
                                        xmin=-1,xmax=15,
                                        ymin=-20,ymax=320,
                                        xtick={2,4,...,14},
                                        minor xtick={1,2,...,15},
                                        ytick={100,200,300},
                                        minor ytick={20,40,...,320},
                                        ]
                                \addplot+[domain = 0:13,->]{50+20*x};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,50) (1,70) (2,90) (4,130) (7,190) (12,290)};
                                \addplot[guideline,-] coordinates {(7,190) (7,290)} node[pos=0.5,above,rotate=90] {$\$100$};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(7,290) (11.5,290)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$5$ weeks};
                                \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Drawing a slope triangle this way is fine for identifying the <q>rise</q> and the <q>run</q>, and is fine for calculating the slope. It's not ideal though, because it puts the vertical change before the horizontal change, and that is inconsistent with other mathematical conventions. This book will generally draw slope triangles with the horizontal change coming first.</p>
            </sidebyside>
        </example>

