        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>The following graph of a line models the amount of gas, in gallons, in a car's tank as it drives. Find the line's slope, and interpret its meaning in this context.</p>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Amount of gas in a car's tank</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,8),(6,6),(9,4)...</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={hours},
                                        ylabel={gas in gallons},
                                        xmin=-1,xmax=11,
                                        ymin=-1,ymax=11,
                                        minor ytick={0,1,...,11},
                                        minor xtick={0,1,...,11},
                                        xtick=,
                                        ytick=]
                                \addplot+[domain=1:8]{-2/3*x+10};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To find a line's slope using its graph, we first identify two points on it, and then draw a slope triangle. Naturally, we would want to choose two points whose <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-coordinates are easy to identify exactly based on the graph. We will pick the two points where <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=6</m>, because they are right on the grid lines:</p>

                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
                    <figure>
                        <caption>A Good Slope Triangle</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,8),(6,6),(9,4)...There is a slope triangle starting from (3,8), passing (6,8) and ending at (6,6). The label from (3,8) to (6,8) is "3 hours"; and the label from (6,8) to (6,6) is "-2 gallons".</description>
                            <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[xlabel={hours},
                                            ylabel={gas in gallons},
                                            xmin=-1,xmax=11,
                                            ymin=-1,ymax=11,
                                            minor ytick={0,1,...,11},
                                            minor xtick={0,1,...,11},
                                            xtick=,
                                            ytick=]
                                    \addplot+[domain=1:8]{-2/3*x+10};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,8) (6,6)};
                                    \addplot[guideline,-] coordinates {(3,8) (6,8)} node[pos=0.5,above] {$3$ hours};
                                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,8) (6,6.3)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$-2$ gallon};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image-code>
                        </image>
                    </figure>

                    <p>Notice that the <em>change</em> in <m>y</m> is negative, because the amount of gas is decreasing. Since we chose points with integer coordiantes, we can easily calculate the slope:<me>\text{slope}=\frac{-2}{3}=-\frac{2}{3}\text{.}</me></p>
                </sidebyside>

                <p>With units, the slope is <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m> <quantity><unit base="gallon" /><per base="hour" /></quantity>. In the given context, this slope implies gas in the tank is <em>decreasing</em> at the rate of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> <quantity><unit base="gallon" /><per base="hour" /></quantity>. Since this slope is written as afraction, there is another way to understand it: gas in the tank is decreasing by <m>2</m> gallons every <m>3</m> hours.</p>

            </solution>
        </example>

        <exercise>
            <webwork>
                <setup>
                    <pg-code>
                        @x=(1999..2013);
                        @y=(17599,17446,17847,17887,17559,18499,18682,19112,19376,20370,19909,19727,20636,20035,20458);
                        $m=Real(244.064)->with(tolType=>'absolute',tolerance=>100);
                        for my$j(0,1){
                          $gr[$j] = init_graph(1998,-2000,2015,25000,axes=>[1999,0],grid=>[17,27],size=>[400,400]);
                          $gr[$j] -> lb('reset');
                          $gr[$j]->h_ticks(0,"black",2000,2005,2010);
                          $gr[$j]->v_ticks(1999,"black",5000,10000,15000,20000);
                          for my$i(2002,2005,2008,2011,2014){$gr[$j]->moveTo($i,-500);$gr[$j]->lineTo($i,500,'black',3);$gr[$j]->lb(new Label($i,1000,$i,'black','center','bottom'));};
                          for my$i(5000,10000,15000,20000){$gr[$j]->moveTo(1998.7,$i);$gr[$j]->lineTo(1999.3,$i,'black',3);$gr[$j]->lb(new Label(1999.5,$i,$i,'black','left','middle'));};
                          $gr[$j]->lb(new Label(2015,-1000,'year','black','right','top'));
                          $gr[$j]->lb(new Label(1999.5,24000,'diagnoses','black','left','top'));
                          add_functions($gr[$j], "$m*x-470583 for x in &lt;1998,2015> using color:blue and weight:2");
                          for my$i(0..14){$gr[$j]->stamps(closed_circle($x[$i],$y[$i],'blue'));};
                        };
                        $gr[1]->stamps(closed_circle(2006,19000,'red'));
                        $gr[1]->stamps(closed_circle(2014,21000,'red'));
                        $gr[1]->moveTo(2006,19000);$gr[1]->lineTo(2006,21000,'red',3);$gr[1]->arrowTo(2014,21000,'red',3);
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>The graph plots the number of invasive cancer diagnoses in Oregon over time, and a trendline has been drawn.</p>

                    <figure>
                        <image pg-name="$gr[0]" />
                    </figure>

                    <p>Estimate the slope of the trend line. Just give the numerical value; the units are provided.</p>
                    <p><var name="$m" width="10" /><m>\,\frac{\text{diagnoses}}{\text{year}}</m></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Do your best to identify two points on the line. With this line, it seems <m>(2006,19000)</m> and <m>(2014,21000)</m> are two such points.</p>
                    <figure>
                        <image pg-name="$gr[1]" />
                    </figure>
                    <p><me>\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{2000}{8}=250</me></p>
                    <p>So the slope is about <m>250</m> diagnoses per year. This is only an estimate since we are not all certain the two points we chose are actually on the line.</p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>

    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="subsection-comparing-slopes">
        <title>Comparing Slopes</title>
        <p>It's useful to understand what it means for different slopes to appear on the same coordinate system.</p>

        <example>
            <p>Effie, Ivan and Cleo are in a foot race. <xref ref="figure-foot-race">Figure</xref> models the distance each has traveled in the first few seconds. Each runner takes a second to accelerate up to their running speed, but then runs at a constant speed. So they are then traveling with a constant rate of change, and the straight line portions of their graphs have a slope. Find each line's slope, and interpret its meaning in this context. What comparisons can you make with these runners?</p>
            <figure xml:id="figure-foot-race">
                <caption>A three-way foot race</caption>
                <image width="50%">
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[xlabel={time (s)},
                                    ylabel={distance (m)},
                                    xmin=-1,xmax=5,
                                    ymin=-2,ymax=15,
                                    minor ytick={0,1,...,15},
                                    minor xtick=,
                                    xtick={0,1,...,5},
                                    ytick={0,5,...,15}]
                            \addplot+[domain=1:5,->]{8/3*(x-1)+1} node[pos=0.5,sloped,below] {Effie};
                            \addplot+[domain=1:5,->]{3.5*(x-1)+1} node[pos=0.5,sloped] {Ivan};
                            \addplot+[domain=1:4.25,->]{4*(x-1)+2} node[pos=0.5,sloped,above] {Cleo};
                            \addplot[primarycurve,-,domain=0:1]{x^(10/3)};
                            \addplot[secondarycurve,-,domain=0:1]{x^3.5};
                            \addplot[tertiarycurve,-,domain=0:1]{2*x^2};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <p>We will draw slope triangles to find each line's slope.</p>

            <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%">
                <caption>Find the Slope of Each Line</caption>

                <figure>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={time (s)},
                                        ylabel={distance (m)},
                                        xmin=-1,xmax=5,
                                        ymin=-2,ymax=15,
                                        minor ytick={0,1,...,15},
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        xtick={0,1,...,5},
                                        ytick={0,5,...,15}]
                                \addplot[primarycurve,domain=1:5,->]{8/3*(x-1)+1} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {Effie};
                                \addplot[primarycurve,-,domain=0:1]{x^(10/3)};
                                \addplot[soliddot]coordinates{(1,1) (4,9)};
                                \addplot[guideline]coordinates{(1,1) (4,1)} node[pos=0.5,above]{$3$ seconds};
                                \addplot[guideline,->]coordinates{(4,1) (4,8.7)} node[pos=0.5,rotate=90,below]{$8$ meters};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <figure>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={time (s)},
                                        ylabel={distance (m)},
                                        xmin=-1,xmax=5,
                                        ymin=-2,ymax=15,
                                        minor ytick={0,1,...,15},
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        xtick={0,1,...,5},
                                        ytick={0,5,...,15}]
                                \addplot[secondarycurve,domain=1:5,->]{3.5*(x-1)+1} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {Ivan};
                                \addplot[secondarycurve,-,domain=0:1]{x^3.5};
                                \addplot[soliddot]coordinates{(1,1) (3,8)};
                                \addplot[guideline]coordinates{(1,1) (3,1)} node[pos=0.5,above]{$2$ seconds};
                                \addplot[guideline,->]coordinates{(3,1) (3,7.7)} node[pos=0.5,rotate=90,below]{$7$ meters};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <figure>
                    <image>
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={time (s)},
                                        ylabel={distance (m)},
                                        xmin=-1,xmax=5,
                                        ymin=-2,ymax=15,
                                        minor ytick={0,1,...,15},
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        xtick={0,1,...,5},
                                        ytick={0,5,...,15}]
                                \addplot[tertiarycurve,domain=1:5,->]{4*(x-1)+2} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {Cleo};
                                \addplot[tertiarycurve,-,domain=0:1]{2*x^2};
                                \addplot[soliddot]coordinates{(1,2) (3,10)};
                                \addplot[guideline]coordinates{(1,2) (3,2)} node[pos=0.5,above]{$2$ seconds};
                                \addplot[guideline,->]coordinates{(3,2) (3,9.7)} node[pos=0.5,rotate=90,below]{$8$ meters};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>

            <p>Using <xref ref="equation-slope-definition">Formula</xref>, we have:<ul>
                <li>Effie's slope is <m>\frac{8}{3}\approx2.666</m> meters per second</li>
                <li>Ivan's slope is <m>\frac{7}{2}=3.5</m> meters per second</li>
                <li>Cleo's slope is <m>\frac{8}{2}=4</m> meters per second</li>
            </ul></p>

            <p>In a time-distance graph, the slope of a line represents speed. The slopes in these examples and the running speeds of these runners are both measured in <quantity><unit base="meter"/><per base="second"/></quantity>. Another important relationship we can see is that, the more sharply a line is slanted, the bigger the slope is. This should make sense because for each passing second, the faster person travels longer, making a slope triangle's height taller. This means that, numerically, we can tell that Cleo is the fastest runner (and Effie is the slowest) just by comparing the slopes <m>4>3.5>2.666</m>.</p>
        </example>

    </subsection>


    <subsection>
        <title>Finding Slope by Two Given Points</title>

        <p>Several times in this section we computed a slope by drawing a slope triangle. That's not really neessary if you have coordinates for two points that a line passes through. In fact, sometimes it's impractical to draw a slope triangle.<fn>For instance if you only have specific information about two points that are too close together to draw a triangle, or if you cannot clearly see precise coordinates where you might start and stop your slope triangle.</fn> Here we will stress how to find a line's slope without drawing a slope triangle.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="WkspBxrzuZo" />
        </figure>

        <example>
            <p>Your neighbor planted a sapling from <url href="http://portlandnursery.com/">Portland Nursery</url><fn>A Passion for Plants. A Nursery for Plant People.</fn> in his front yard. Ever since, for several years now, it has been growing at a constant rate. By the end of the third year, the tree was <quantity><mag>15</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity> tall; by the end of the sixth year, the tree was <quantity><mag>27</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity> tall. What's the tree's rate of growth (<ie /> the slope)?</p>

            <p>We <em>could</em> sketch a graph for this scenario, and include a slope triangle. If we did that, it would look like this:</p>

            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">
                <figure>
                    <caption>Height of a Tree</caption>
                    <image>
                        <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15) to (6,15) is "6-3=3 years"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "27-15=12 feet".</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={years since planting},
                                        ylabel={height (ft)},
                                        xmin=-1,xmax=9,
                                        ymin=-3,ymax=30,
                                        minor ytick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        xtick={0,1,...,8},
                                        ytick={0,3,...,27},
                                        clip=false]
                                \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$3$ years};
                                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90] {$12$ ft};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>By the slope triangle and <xref ref="equation-slope-definition">Equation</xref> we have:<md>
                    <mrow>\text{slope}=m\amp =\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp =\frac{12}{3}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp =4</mrow>
                </md>So the tree is growing at a rate of <quantity><mag>4</mag><unit base="foot" /><per base="year" /></quantity>.</p>
            </sidebyside>

            <p>But hold on. Did we really <em>need</em> this picture? The <q>rise</q> of <m>12</m> came from a subtraction of two <m>y</m>-values: <m>27-15</m>. And the <q>run</q> of <m>3</m> came from a subtraction of two <m>x</m>-values: <m>6-3</m>.</p>

            <p>Here is a picture-free approach. We know that after <quantity><mag>3</mag><unit base="year" /></quantity>, the height is <quantity><mag>15</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity>. As an ordered pair, that information gives us the point <m>(3,15)</m> which we can label as <m>(\overset{x_1}{3},\overset{y_1}{15})</m>. Similarly, the background information tells us to consider <m>(6,27)</m>, which we lable as <m>(\overset{x_2}{6},\overset{y_2}{27})</m>. Here, <m>x_1</m> and <m>y_1</m> represent the first point's <m>x</m>-value and <m>y</m>-value, and <m>x_2</m> and <m>y_2</m> represent the second point's <m>x</m>-value and <m>y</m>-value.</p>

            <aside>
                <title>Subscript</title>
                <p>It's important to use subscript instead of superscript here, because <m>y^2</m> means to take the number <m>y</m> and square it. Whereas <m>y_2</m> tells you that there are at lest two <m>y</m>-values in the conversation, and <m>y_2</m> is the second of them.</p>
            </aside>

            <p>Now we can write an alternative to <xref ref="equation-slope-definition">Equation</xref>:<men xml:id="equation-slope-formula">\text{slope}=m=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</men>This is known as the <term>slope formula</term>.<index><main>slope</main><sub>formula</sub></index> The following graph will help you understand why this formula works. Basically, we are still using a slope triangle to calculate the slope.</p>

            <sidebyside xml:id="figure-slope-formula" widths="47% 47%">
                <caption>Understanding the slope formula</caption>

                <figure>
                    <image>
                        <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15) to (6,15) is "6-3=3 years"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "27-15=12 feet".</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={years since planting},
                                        ylabel={height (ft)},
                                        xmin=-1,xmax=9,
                                        ymin=-3,ymax=30,
                                        minor ytick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        xtick={},
                                        ytick={},
                                        clip=false]
                                \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=left] {$6-3$\\${}=3$ years};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90,align=left] {$27-15$\\${}=12$ ft};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <figure>
                    <image>
                        <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15) to (6,15) is "x2-x1"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "y2-y1".</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,xmax=9,
                                        ymin=-3,ymax=30,
                                        minor ytick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        xtick={},
                                        ytick={},
                                        clip=false]
                                \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(x_1,y_1)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(x_2,y_2)$};
                                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=left] {$x_2-x_1$};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90,align=left] {$y_2-y_1$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
        </example>

        <p>The beauty of the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" autoname="title">slope formula</xref> is that to find a line's slope, we don't need to draw a slope triangle any more. Let's look at an example.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>A line passes the points <m>(-5,25)</m> and <m>(4,-2)\text{.}</m> Find this line's slope.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>If you are new to this formula, it's important to label each number before using the formula. The two given points are:<me>(\overset{x_1}{-5},\overset{y_1}{25}) \text{ and } (\overset{x_2}{4},\overset{y_2}{-2})</me>Now apply the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" autoname="title">slope formula</xref>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-2-(25)}{4-(-5)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-27}{9}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>Note that we used parentheses when substituting in <m>x_1</m> and <m>y_1</m>. This is a good habit to protect yourself from making errors with subtraction and double negatives.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>

